Lesson 5

Multivariate Data

  • How to conduct EDA going beyond 2D analysis?
  • Moira uses COLOR of points to represent the 3rd variable

Third Qualitative Variable

suppressMessages(library(dplyr))
pf <- read.csv('pseudo_facebook.tsv', sep='\t')

pf.fc_by_age_gender <- pf %>%
  filter(!is.na(gender)) %>% # there are some NAs in the header/footer output
  group_by(age, gender) %>%
  summarise(mean_friend_count = mean(as.numeric(friend_count)),
            median_friend_count = median(as.numeric(friend_count)),
            n = n()) %>%
  ungroup(age,gender) %>% 
  # need ungroup because summarise() will remove one layer of grouping when it runs, so it'll remove the gender layer. So we also need to ungroup the age layer. 
  arrange(age, gender)

Plotting Conditional Summaries

library(ggplot2)

ggplot(aes(x=age, y=median_friend_count), 
       data = subset(pf.fc_by_age_gender,!is.na(gender))) + 
  geom_line(aes(color=gender))

Ration Plot

  • how many more times friends do females have than men?
  • convert data from wide to long format: spread column data to be its own columns so male/female are values rather than column names
# Reshaping data 
library(tidyr)

pf.fc_by_age_gender.wide <- spread(subset(pf.fc_by_age_gender, 
       select = c('gender', 'age', 'median_friend_count'),
       !is.na(gender)), 
       gender, median_friend_count) %>%
  mutate(ratio = female / male)
# Ratio plot 
ggplot(aes(x=age, y=ratio), 
       data = subset(pf.fc_by_age_gender.wide)) + 
  geom_line() + 
  geom_hline(yintercept = 1, linetype=2)

Third Quantitative Variable

pf$year_joined <- with(pf,floor(2014 - (tenure/365)))

Cut a Variable

  • combining bins because some years don’t have a lot of data
  • turns tenure into a categorical variable because bins are not the same size
pf$year_joined.bucket <- cut(pf$year_joined, breaks = c(2004,2009,2011,2012,2014))

Plotting it All Together

  • we took year_joined and created year_joined_bucket
  • use year_joined_bucket variable to create overlain line graphs similar to gender
  • use fun.y = median and summary
  • create friend_count (y) vs age (x) across each year_joined_bucket
table(pf$year_joined.bucket)
## 
## (2004,2009] (2009,2011] (2011,2012] (2012,2014] 
##        6669       15308       33366       43658
ggplot(aes(x = age, y = friend_count),
       data = subset(pf, !is.na(year_joined.bucket))) +
  geom_line(aes(color = year_joined.bucket), stat = 'summary', fun.y = median)

# CODE FOR GENDER RE-USED

#   geom_line(aes(color = gender), stat = 'summary', fun.y = median)

Plot the Grand Mean

  • users with longer tenures tend to have higher friend counts
  • as predicted!
  • change median calc to means
  • plot grand mean as well … do it across all buckets
ggplot(aes(x = age, y = friend_count),
       data = subset(pf, !is.na(year_joined.bucket))) +
  geom_line(aes(color = year_joined.bucket), stat = 'summary', fun.y = mean) +
  geom_line(stat = 'summary', linetype = 2, fun.y = mean)

# can see much of the data comes from members in recent cohorts.. this is the type of high-level observation you want to make as you explore more data

Friending Rate

  • how many friends does a user have, for each day since they started using the service?
  • subset the data so only considering users with at least 1 day of tenure
  • what’s median rate? what’s max rate?
with(subset(pf,tenure >= 1), summary(friend_count/tenure))
##     Min.  1st Qu.   Median     Mean  3rd Qu.     Max. 
##   0.0000   0.0775   0.2205   0.6096   0.5658 417.0000
  # max is definitely an outlier because 3rd quartile is 0.5

Friendships Initiated

  • create line graph of friendships initiated per day vs tenure
  • make use of variables tenure, friendships_initiated, and year_joined.bucket
  • color of each part of one line should correspond with each bucket of year_joined
  • subset data to only consider users with at least 1 day of tenure
ggplot(aes(x = tenure, y = friendships_initiated/tenure),
       data = subset(pf, tenure>=1)) +
  geom_line(aes(color=year_joined.bucket), stat = 'summary', fun.y = mean) 

# people with more tenure (on farther right of graph) tend to initiate fewer friendships (lower heights), which makes sense since they already have a bunch of friends 

  # can also create a smooth version of this graph by replacing geom_line with geom_smooth... note that you don't include stat = 'summary' and fun.y = mean because geom_smooth() automatically chooses a function to smooth the data based on the data values 

ggplot(aes(x = tenure, y = friendships_initiated/tenure),
       data = subset(pf, tenure>=1)) +
  geom_smooth(aes(color=year_joined.bucket)) 
## `geom_smooth()` using method = 'gam'

Bias-Variance Tradeoff Revisited

  • bin values on x-axis to remove some of the noise
  • manipulate the x-values somehow
ggplot(aes(x = tenure, y = friendships_initiated / tenure),
       data = subset(pf, tenure >= 1)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = year_joined.bucket),
            stat = 'summary',
            fun.y = mean)

ggplot(aes(x = 7 * round(tenure / 7), y = friendships_initiated / tenure),
       data = subset(pf, tenure > 0)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = year_joined.bucket),
            stat = "summary",
            fun.y = mean)

ggplot(aes(x = 30 * round(tenure / 30), y = friendships_initiated / tenure),
       data = subset(pf, tenure > 0)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = year_joined.bucket),
            stat = "summary",
            fun.y = mean)

ggplot(aes(x = 90 * round(tenure / 90), y = friendships_initiated / tenure),
       data = subset(pf, tenure > 0)) +
  geom_line(aes(color = year_joined.bucket),
            stat = "summary",
            fun.y = mean)

Sean’s NFL Fan Sentiment Study

  • 1 day moving averages helps remove some noise in the data
  • creating a model that predicts sentiment as a function of time
  • very broad model shows excitement is greatest in the beginning, but we’re not seeing the highs and lows of game day itself
  • 7 day moving average is better because you can see impacts on/after gamedays when you win and lose
  • moving averages let the data mainly speak for itself.. lots of variance and error
  • once you add lags to moving average, you get smoother plots but data is becoming more biased (hence the variance-bias trade-off)
  • adding splines lets you get best of both worlds

Introducing the Yogurt Data Set

  • data about various yogurt purchases across multiple households over a period of time
  • includes price data
  • includes same households making multiple purchases as separate points, unlike fb data set
  • make sure that id says factor, else convert it

Histograms Revisited

# load data, convert id to a factor variable 
yo <- read.csv('yogurt.csv')
yo$id <- factor(yo$id)

# create histogram of yogurt prices 
ggplot(data=yo, aes(x=price)) + geom_histogram(binwidth=1)

Number of Purchases

  • if we just look at 5 number summary, wouldn’t have noticed the discreteness
  • one clue of discreteness is that 75th percentile is same as max
  • use transform function to create a new variable called all_purchases that gives total count of yogurts for each observation/household
yo <- transform(yo, all.purchases = strawberry+blueberry+pina.colada+plain+mixed.berry)

Prices over Time

  • see how prices of yogurts bought has changed over time
  • scatterplot of price over time
ggplot(data=yo, aes(x=time, y=price)) + geom_point(alpha=1/10)

# the most common prices are increasing over time, other smaller price points scattered, probably due to sales, discounts, etc.

Sampling Observations

  • subsamples are helpful for plotting raw data and getting a deeper look without slowing down analysis by looking at entire data set

Looking at Samples of Households

set.seed(4230)
sample.ids <- sample(levels(yo$id), 16)

# use code from above, but subset the 16 households we've sampled

ggplot(aes(x=time, y=price), 
       data = subset(yo, id %in% sample.ids)) + # syntax loops over IDs to focus on households we care about 
  facet_wrap( ~ id) + 
  geom_line() + 
  geom_point(aes(size = all.purchases), pch = 1)

    # considers number of items for each point on that plot 
# do again with a different 16 households
set.seed(9111)
sample.ids <- sample(levels(yo$id), 16)

ggplot(aes(x=time, y=price), 
       data = subset(yo, id %in% sample.ids)) + 
  facet_wrap( ~ id) + 
  geom_line() + 
  geom_point(aes(size = all.purchases), pch = 1)

The Limits of Cross Sectional Data

  • couldn’t generate this faceted data for facebook data because we didn’t have multiple snapshots of the same individuals (data about individuals over a period of time)

Many Variables

  • EDA allowed us to explore some pre-chosen variables
  • in choosing 3rd/4th variable to plot, we used our domain knowledge
  • when we don’t have domain knowledge, you can use some visualizations to figure out which other variables to test… like maybe you have 100 different variables, or are just looking for interesting relationships
  • this is where scatterplot matrices come into use

Scatterplot Matrix

  • grid of scatterplots doing every variable combination
  • scatterplots are great, but not suited for every single variable, like categorical ones
  • can subset those out if you’d like
  • cannot do much customization for scatter plots themselves
  • can choose an overall theme for the grid

Even More Variables

  • interesting data to overlay is genomic data sets
  • gene expression in tumors
  • 6800 genes compared to reference sample

Heat Maps

  • an “overexpressed” gene is in red while an “underexpressed” gene is in blue
  • dense display… shows just first 200 genes of over 6000
  • genomic datasets of this kind are only getting larger
  • there are other datasets that look like this, e.g. UX data from a/b experiments
nci <- read.table("nci.tsv")
colnames(nci) <- c(1:64)
# melt the data to long format
library(reshape2)
## 
## Attaching package: 'reshape2'
## The following object is masked from 'package:tidyr':
## 
##     smiths
nci.long.samp <- melt(as.matrix(nci[1:200,]))
names(nci.long.samp) <- c("gene", "case", "value")
head(nci.long.samp)
##   gene case  value
## 1    1    1  0.300
## 2    2    1  1.180
## 3    3    1  0.550
## 4    4    1  1.140
## 5    5    1 -0.265
## 6    6    1 -0.070
# create heat map 
ggplot(aes(y = gene, x = case, fill = value),
  data = nci.long.samp) +
  geom_tile() +
  scale_fill_gradientn(colours = colorRampPalette(c("blue", "red"))(100))

Analyzing Three of More Variables

  • can include third variable via multiple lines colored differently
  • use subset( to remove NA or put in a certain qualifier
  • change data between wide and long formats as needed
  • data about the same subject over multiple periods of time allows you to get more information than taking means/medians of snapshots of many individuals
  • can add a baseline via geom_hline(y-intercept = )
  • can create new variables for a data set by transforming other variables / applying functions between other variables
  • can plot grand means / medians by doing stat = ‘summary’ and fun.y = mean as another layer to the main ggplot (don’t need to create a new variable in the data frame again). usually use linetype to distinguish that
  • can also use color to differentiate along one set of data (e.g. grand means), so line changes color as you travel along x-axis
  • smooth by manipulating x variable via rounding OR using geom_smooth
  • create multiple subplots using facet, usually after taking a sub-sample
  • compare correlations among multiple variables simultaneously via ggpairs (in library GGally)
  • can analyze even more variables via heat maps
